 <a href="/content/introduction-mapreduce-hadoop-linux" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"><img src="http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/ufiles/imagecache/teaser/nodeimage/story/11456f3.jpg" alt="" title=""  class="imagecache imagecache-teaser" width="100" height="100" /></a> 
  
  


      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/content/introduction-mapreduce-hadoop-linux" title="Introduction to MapReduce with Hadoop on Linux">Introduction to MapReduce with Hadoop on Linux</a>
    </h2>
  
  

  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
		By <a href="/users/adam-monsen" title="View user profile.">Adam Monsen</a>&nbsp;<!--|
		Jun 05, 2013 -->
     
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_783 first"><a href="/tag/forensics" rel="tag" title="">Forensics</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_864"><a href="/tag/hadoop" rel="tag" title="">Hadoop</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_241 last active"><a href="/tag/hpc" rel="tag" title="" class="active">HPC</a></li>
</ul></div>
      
  	 </div>
    </div>
  
  
    


  <div class="content">

    
    
            
                    <a href="/content/introduction-mapreduce-hadoop-linux" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"></a>        
        

<p>
When your data and work grow, and you still want to produce results in a
timely manner, you start to think big. Your one beefy server reaches its
limits. You need a way to spread your work across many computers. You
truly need to scale out.
<span class="read-more"><a href="/content/introduction-mapreduce-hadoop-linux"> more>></a></span></p>
  </div>



